{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499910"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:05:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:05:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1582"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1582"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.32,0.55,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1582"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107164"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1582"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1582"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89616"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"845"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34995"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107164"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-year history of worsening thickening, dryness and blistering of both hands. He describes associated itching and burning sensations. He has had dry skin on his palms for five years and has received multiple courses of oral antibiotics for suspected skin infections. He has a history of mild asthma and excessive sweating of his palms and underarms. He does not take any regular medications. Both of his children have eczema. He works as a chef and smokes 20 cigarettes per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple small vesicles across both palms and fingers with background erythema and fissuring of the skin (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hand, foot and mouth disease","Varicella","Lichen nitidus","Pompholyx (dyshidrotic eczema)","Bullous pemphigoid"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of \u003Cstrong\u003Epompholyx\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as dyshidrotic eczema. The chronic nature, palmar distribution of vesicles, association with hyperhidrosis, and family history of atopy are characteristic. His occupation as a chef, involving frequent hand-washing and exposure to irritants, is a significant contributing factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPompholyx affects approximately 5-20% of patients with hand eczema and typically presents in young adults. The exact cause remains unclear but is thought to be multifactorial, involving genetic predisposition, environmental triggers, and altered immune responses. Common triggers include stress, contact with metals (particularly nickel), seasonal changes, and occupational exposures. The condition often follows a chronic, relapsing course with significant impact on quality of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHand, foot and mouth disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects children and presents as an acute illness with fever and vesicles around the mouth, hands, and feet. The chronic nature and occupational association make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricella\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a widespread, pruritic vesicular eruption affecting the entire body. It is typically acute and self-limiting, unlike this patient\u0027s chronic course.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELichen nitidus\u003C/strong\u003E presents with small, flesh-coloured papules typically on the forearms, genitals, and trunk. It does not cause vesicles or primarily affect the palms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBullous pemphigoid\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects older adults and presents with large, tense blisters predominantly on the flexural aspects of limbs. It is not typically limited to the palms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of pompholyx includes avoiding triggers, using emollients, and applying potent topical corticosteroids. Severe cases may require systemic therapy such as oral corticosteroids or immunosuppressants. Occupational modification and treatment of hyperhidrosis may also be beneficial.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pompholyx (dyshidrotic eczema) is characterised by recurrent vesicles on palms and soles, often associated with hyperhidrosis.","Risk factors include personal or family history of atopy and occupational exposure to irritants.","Treatment involves potent topical corticosteroids, emollients, and consideration of systemic therapy for severe cases."],"references":["Wollina U. Pompholyx: a review of clinical features, differential diagnosis, and management. Am J Clin Dermatol. 2010;11(5):305-14. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20642293/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89616"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1582"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18675"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media"